			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/51042462c6b3d20f5e7ca4eeb1807986?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/51042462c6b3d20f5e7ca4eeb1807986?s=80&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://kevin-standlee.livejournal.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Kevin</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-428725">
				August 25, 2015 at 20:15					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>James:</p>
<p>What&#8217;s your point? Every single member of WSFS who wanted to vote had his/her vote counted. Nobody was prohibited from voting. Are you suggesting that anyone who wanted to buy a membership in WSFS and vote was prohibited from doing so? A large number of people joined WSFS and expressed their opinion that all of the finalists in five categories were not worthy of the organization&#8217;s highest honor. There&#8217;s nothing wrong with this, and it&#8217;s completely within the organization&#8217;s rules, just as it was within the rules for many like-minded people to nominate works that they liked, no matter how much other people disliked them.</p>
<p>Nothing prohibited by the WSFS rules has happened. The members of WSFS acted in an open, democratic manner, in a system whose rules are open and public, and that can be changed if enough member of the organization want them to change. There&#8217;s no secret cabal or shadowy Board of Directors making the decisions.</p>
</div>

